*[HelpRoot_Dev_Integration\IS__mng_Push_Notificatons|Configuring Push Notifications]

Acumatica ERP is an application with multitenant architecture, in which any instance includes at least one tenant that is a separate tenant. If you need to create multiple similar tenants, you do not have to configure each tenant from scratch, you can use snapshots instead. {br}
Snapshots provide a way to save full or partial data of your Acumatica ERP tenant, and later restore the tenant to the state it had when the snapshot was taken. Snapshots can be exported from the source tenant and then restored to another tenant, thus speeding up the configuration of a new tenant. Snapshots are stored in the Acumatica ERP database, and you may face with a situation when the database is out of space. As such, it is important to monitor database size and delete unneeded snapshots.{br}
The topics of this chapter explain how to use snapshots, including taking a snapshot, storing it locally or in external storage, importing it to your instance, restoring the data from the snapshot. ==In This Chapter== *[HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Snapshots_GeneralInfo|Using Snapshots: General Information] *:A snapshot is full or partial data of an Acumatica ERP tenant saved locally in the database of an instance to which the tenant belongs, or at specified location. Snapshots can also be used as tenant templates when you need to add new tenants that are similar in configuration to an Acumatica ERP instance. Also, you can use snapshots to set up a test environment for your company where you test the configuration changes required for your company before you apply them to your production tenant. *[HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Snapshots_Export_and_Import_Concept|Using Snapshots: Export and Import] *:Snapshots are stored in database, to free disk space, you can export snapshots to store them in an external storage, and then delete obsolete snapshots. Exported snapshots can later be imported back into the instance. *[HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Snapshots_Modification_of_Content_Options_Concept|Using Snapshots: Custom Snapshot Configurations] *:The contents of the snapshot is the data from SQL database tables that are included in the snapshot. The list of tables to be included to a snapshot is defined by a content option (or export mode) that you select when you take a snapshot. There is a predefined set of options that you can select in the '''Export Mode''' box of the '''Create Snapshot''' dialog box. If the predefined options do not suite your need, for example, for data security reasons, you can configure and add custom options. *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Snapshot_Sensitive_Data|Examples of Sensitive Data Preservation in Snapshots] *:Protection of sensitive data is critical to organizations and to users. Which data must be protected depends on many factors, including regulation (which is often mandatory), organization policy, contractual obligations, and user expectations. Because the snapshots may copy data you identify as sensitive, Acumatica ERP provides a way to exclude such data from the snapshots. You can preserve the data from particular SQL tables down to particular table fields by configuring snapshot configuration files. Use the following examples to better understand and configure snapshot configuration files. *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Add|To Take a Snapshot] *:To take a snapshot of the tenant configuration and data, you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. Published customization are also included in the snapshot. *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Visibility|To Toggle the Visibility of a Snapshot] *:In a multitenant configuration, you can toggle the visibility of snapshots on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form to group them by tenant, as described below. You can distinguish snapshots with different visibility by checking the state of the '''Tenant ID''' column on the '''Snapshots''' tab: *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Export|To Export a Snapshot] *:You can export a snapshot by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Import|To Import a Snapshot] *:To import a snapshot, you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. A snapshot can be restored in a new database only if the version of the application match the version of the snapshot (that is, the version of the application used to take the snapshot). You can view the version of the snapshot in the ''manifest.xml'' file in the snapshot. *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Restore|To Restore a Snapshot] *:You can restore data to a tenant from any snapshot that is visible in the tenant by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Delete|To Delete a Snapshot] *:All the snapshots you take are stored in the database of your Acumatica ERP instance. To reduce the size of the database, you can delete obsolete snapshots by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form.

A snapshot is full or partial data of an Acumatica ERP tenant saved locally in the database of an instance to which the tenant belongs, or at specified location. Snapshots can also be used as tenant templates when you need to add new tenants that are similar in configuration to an Acumatica ERP instance. Also, you can use snapshots to set up a test environment for your company where you test the configuration changes required for your company before you apply them to your production tenant. {br}

A tenant used to take a snapshot is called source tenant and tenant where you plan to restore a snapshot is called destination tenant. Source and destination tenants may belong to the same instance or to different instances.{br}{TOC}
==Learning Objectives==
In this chapter, you will learn how to do the following:[anchor|#ul_dmx_2lv_pr]
*Take a snapshot of tenant specific content
*Export a snapshot to an external storage
*Review the ''manifest.xml'' file of snapshot to find out snapshot details 
*Import a snapshot
*Restore a snapshot for a destination tenant

==Applicable Scenarios==
You use snapshots in the following cases:[anchor|#_7165d0ed-fbf9-4bca-b563-a0155c7a9310]
*Before starting a user acceptance testing (UAT) phase of an implementation, you, as an implementation consultant, need to prepare a test instance to perform UAT. The test instance should be identical to the one you have configured for production. You take a snapshot of the production tenant and restore it on a test instance dedicated for UAT.
*Your company decided to try a new Acumatica ERP feature on the copy of your production tenant and you, as a system administrator, was requested to create a test tenant and port production data to it. You take a snapshot of the production tenant and restore it on a test instance dedicated for testing.
*You, as a system administrator, was requested to create a tenant with a training dataset for a new employee of your company. You download a snapshot with training dataset and restore it on the test tenant dedicated to the employee training.

==Snapshot Contents==
The contents of the snapshot is the data from SQL database tables that are included in the snapshot. The list of tables to be included to a snapshot is defined by a content option that you select when you take a snapshot in the '''Export Mode''' box of the '''Create Snapshot''' dialog box. The following content options are available by default: [anchor|#ul_nhd_hzs_tr]
*''Full'': All data related to the tenant
*''Full except Attachments and Wiki'': The full data related to the tenant, excluding attachments and wiki articles
*''Full except Attachments'': The full data related to the tenant, excluding attachments
*''Settings and Business Accounts'': The tenant&rsquo;s complete set of configuration settings and business accounts, including attachments
*''Settings and Business Accounts except Attachments'': The tenant&rsquo;s complete set of configuration settings and business accounts, excluding attachments
*''Settings except Attachments'': The tenant&rsquo;s configuration settings, excluding attachments
*''Settings only'': The tenant&rsquo;s configuration settings, including attachments

You select a content option depending on the intended use of the snapshot. If you need a snapshot for testing purposes or for making a tenant template, then configuration settings may be enough for you. If you need a complete copy of a tenant, then you should select one of the options that include all tenant data. {br}

You can add a custom content option, if the predefined set does not suite your needs, for example, for data security reasons. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Snapshots_Modification_of_Content_Options_Concept|Using Snapshots: Custom Snapshot Configurations].
==Snapshot Creation==
You take a snapshot of the tenant configuration and data by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. For a snapshot, you specify which data you want to include by selecting one of the available content options. Data from published customizations is a part of the database and is always included in snapshots. When you take a snapshot, any previously taken snapshots are not included in the new snapshot.[anchor|#_236b4a5b-3a04-44a4-b8ab-c7c694d3be9a]((({S:Hint}You can have a virtually unlimited number of snapshots. The only limitation is disk space: Snapshots are stored in the database, thus occupying disk space. We recommend that before you take or import a snapshot, you open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_25|Space Usage] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203525|SM203525]) form and make sure that you have enough free space in the Acumatica ERP database. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Database_Size_Monitoring|Database Size Monitoring and Management].
)))
The process of creating a snapshot may take a significant amount of time because the database tables are copied one by one for a snapshot, and this process sometimes results in errors. For example, a user may introduce changes to documents that have been partially copied; consequently, the data in the snapshot would be corrupted. Therefore, if you intend to restore the snapshot in a production system, we strongly recommend that you create snapshots in maintenance mode (that is, when the system is locked out for maintenance, as described in [HelpRoot_Install\Updating__how_Enable_Lockout|To Schedule the System Lockout]).{br}

For testing purposes, you can create snapshots without first locking out the system. In this case, a warning message will appear, and the system will mark this snapshot as unsafe. (The '''Is Safe''' column on the '''Snapshots''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] form reflects whether the snapshot is safe or not.)((({S:Warn}Because the process of taking a snapshot could result in errors, we do not recommend that you use snapshots to back up data. We recommend that you instead use database management applications to back up the database of your Acumatica ERP instance.
)))
==Snapshot Storage and Update==
Once a snapshot is created, it appears on the '''Snapshots''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. Tenant snapshots are stored in the database as tenants with special tenant IDs (negative integers). When you update the application and the database, the stored snapshots are updated as well.{br}

To free disk space, you can export snapshots to store them in an external storage, and then delete obsolete snapshots. Exported snapshots can later be imported back into the application. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Snapshots_Export_and_Import_Concept|Using Snapshots: Export and Import].((({S:Warn}Snapshots stored in an external storage are not updated when you update your application instance.
)))
Deleting a snapshot is a permanent operation—you won&rsquo;t be able to recover a deleted snapshot. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Delete|To Delete a Snapshot].
==Snapshot Visibility Across Tenants==
In a multitenant configuration, you can sign in to one tenant, and then take a snapshot of any tenant available to you, be it the tenant you signed in to or another tenant that you can access. The snapshots you take are stored within the tenant you are signed in to (the ''base'' tenant); you won&rsquo;t be able to access them if you sign in to another tenant.{br}

Within the base tenant, when a snapshot is taken, it is associated with its source tenant. That is, to see the snapshot in the list on the '''Snapshots''' tab you should select its source tenant in the '''Tenant ID''' box of the Summary area of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. While a snapshot is associated with a tenant (the associated tenant is displayed for the snapshot in the '''Tenant ID''' column on the '''Snapshots''' tab) you can export or restore its snapshot only for the associated tenant. {br}

To make the snapshot available for export or restoration regardless of the selected tenant, you can change the visibility of the snapshot, by clicking '''Change Visibility''' on the table toolbar of the '''Snapshots''' tab for a selected snapshot. The system removes the association and clears the '''Tenant ID''' column for the snapshot. Then, the snapshot is available on the '''Snapshots''' tab regardless of the tenant you select in the '''Tenant ID''' box of the Summary area. You can export or restore the snapshot for any tenant selected in the '''Tenant ID''' box of the Summary area.{br}

Also, you can move a snapshot between tenants, for example for security reasons. You take a snapshot of a source tenant, remove the association, select a destination tenant in the '''Tenant ID''' box of the Summary area and click '''Change Visibility''' on the table toolbar of the '''Snapshots''' tab for the selected snapshot. The system associates the snapshot with the destination tenant and the snapshot is not available for other tenants of the system, even its source tenant. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Visibility|To Toggle the Visibility of a Snapshot].
==Snapshot Restoration==
When you take a snapshot, it is saved to the tenant you are currently signed in to. In a multitenant configuration, you can sign in to one tenant and move or share snapshots between other tenants that you can access by changing snapshot visibility. Alternatively, you can export a snapshot and store it in an external location and import it to the needed tenant. For details, on exporting and importing snapshots, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Snapshots_Export_and_Import_Concept|Using Snapshots: Export and Import].{br}

You select a tenant for which you want to restore a snapshot in the '''Tenant ID''' box of the Summary area of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. The system displays snapshots available for the selected tenant in the list on the '''Snapshots''' tab. These snapshots can be imported, moved from another tenant or shared between all tenants of the instance. By restoring a snapshot, you set the tenant data (selected in the '''Tenant ID''' box of the Summary area of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] form) to the state of a source tenant when the snapshot was taken. {br}

If you restore an unsafe snapshot (one that was not taken in maintenance mode), the system displays a warning message, and adds a warning to the '''Tools''' > '''About...''' box. We do not recommend that you restore unsafe snapshots in production system because these snapshots can create corrupted data.[anchor|#_93d01f56-d253-4a91-94d2-c578f951e53b]((({S:Hint}You can have a virtually unlimited number of snapshots. The only limitation is disk space: Snapshots are stored in the database, thus occupying disk space. We recommend that before you take or import a snapshot, you open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_25|Space Usage] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203525|SM203525]) form and make sure that you have enough free space in the Acumatica ERP database. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Database_Size_Monitoring|Database Size Monitoring and Management].
)))

Snapshots are stored in database, to free disk space, you can export snapshots to store them in an external storage, and then delete obsolete snapshots. Exported snapshots can later be imported back into the instance. {br}
Also, to move a snapshot to another instance, you export the snapshot from the source instance and import it to the destination instance.{br}
In this topic you will read about details of snapshot export and import.[anchor|#export_snapshot] ==Snapshot Export== To be exported to external storage, a snapshot should be ''prepared''—that is, the snapshot&rsquo;s data should be saved to a file. When a snapshot is exported, the system copies the prepared file to an external storage; the snapshot itself remains in the database. For the detailed procedure, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__how_Snapshots_Export|To Export a Snapshot].{br}
An exported snapshot is saved as an archive in ''.zip'' format. It contains the exported data in a collection of either ''.adb'' or ''.xml'' files and the description of the snapshot in ''manifest.xml''. ==Validation of Snapshot Before Import== ''Manifest.xml'' carries the snapshot details generated when the snapshot was created. If you need to import a snapshot data to a tenant from an instance that is different from the instance of a source tenant, you need to define whether the destination instance is compatible with the snapshot. In the ''manifest.xml'' file you can find the following information that helps you understand whether your instance is compatible with a snapshot:[anchor|#_c1761032-c1d2-4a74-b7e4-fe978992535e] *The Acumatica ERP version of the instance that has been used to prepare the snapshot (instance of the source tenant). The version of an instance of the tenant where you plan to restore the snapshot (destination tenant) must be the same. *The snapshot contents, that is, export mode selected during the snapshot creation. *Whether a snapshot was created in system maintenance mode. Such snapshots are marked as safe. *List of customization packages that were applied to the instance of the sources tenant and whose custom data was included to the snapshot. These packages will be added to the destination tenant. You will specify whether to include custom data during snapshot import. [anchor|#import_snapshot] ==Snapshot Import== You can restore snapshots that are saved in database of the instance of a destination tenant. {br}
For this, you import a snapshot to a selected tenant on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_20|Tenants] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203520|SM203520]) form. The version of the snapshot (that is, the version of the instance used to take the snapshot) must match the version of the destination application instance.[anchor|#_6836a3b9-29f8-4486-a057-8056fef1c6e1]((({S:Hint}You can have a virtually unlimited number of snapshots. The only limitation is disk space: Snapshots are stored in the database, thus occupying disk space. We recommend that before you take or import a snapshot, you open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_25|Space Usage] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203525|SM203525]) form and make sure that you have enough free space in the Acumatica ERP database. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Database_Size_Monitoring|Database Size Monitoring and Management]. ))) When you import a snapshot, you need to specify whether a system should import custom data from the snapshot or not. Custom data is data entered to the fields that were added by customization packages applied to the instance where the snapshot was taken. This operation is controlled with the '''Include Data From Custom Columns''' check box in the import dialog box. {br}
Also, you need to specify whether the system should preliminarily match the data from the snapshot with the database structure in your current Acumatica ERP instance, to reveal any conflicts before the system imports the snapshot. This operation is controlled with the '''Check Database Structure Before Import''' check box in the import dialog box {br}
Customizations may include changes in the database structure (such as changing a field length). These changes may cause conflicts during the insertion of data from the snapshot to your current Acumatica ERP instance (for example, if the length of the inserted field exceeds the maximum length in the database of your current Acumatica ERP instance). When this check is performed and there are conflicts, the system returns an error message that lists all fields from the snapshot that have caused the conflicts. You can resolve these conflicts by changing the database structure in your current Acumatica ERP instance.((({S:Hint}If you have access to the destination instance database, you can resolve conflicts directly in database management studio, otherwise you can develop a customization package with a script that resolves the conflicts. ))) The following table summarizes our recommendations regarding selection of operations during importing a snapshot in dependance on set of customization packages applied to a source instance when a snapshot was taken and the one applied to destination instance when a snapshot is to be imported.[anchor|#_72bf167b-ce02-4baf-bc2e-6a86cc7cbd4f] ===Recommended settings for importing snapshots=== {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Instance of Source Tenant !width="20%" ! Instance of Destination Tenant !width="20%" ! Settings !width="20%" ! Source and Destination Tenants Belong to the Same Instance !width="20%" ! Source and Destination Tenants Belong to the Different Instances |- | rowspan="2" | No customization packages had been applied when a snapshot was taken. | rowspan="2" | No customization packages are applied when a snapshot is to be imported. | '''Include Data From Custom Columns''' | The system ignores the value. | The system ignores the value. |- | '''Check Database Structure Before Import''' | The system ignores the value. | The system ignores the value. |- | rowspan="2" | No customization packages had been applied when a snapshot was taken. | rowspan="2" | Some customization packages are applied when a snapshot is to be imported. | '''Include Data From Custom Columns''' | The scenario is not applicable. | ''Cleared'' |- | '''Check Database Structure Before Import''' | The scenario is not applicable. | ''Selected'' |- | rowspan="2" | Some customization packages had been applied to when a snapshot was taken. | rowspan="2" | No customization packages are applied when a snapshot is to be imported. | '''Include Data From Custom Columns''' | The scenario is not applicable. | ''Cleared'' |- | '''Check Database Structure Before Import''' | The scenario is not applicable. | ''Selected'' |- | rowspan="2" | | colspan="2" | The set of customization packages applied to the source instance when a snapshot was taken is the same as the set of packages applied to the destination instance when the snapshot is to be imported. | '''Include Data From Custom Columns''' | ''Selected'' | ''Selected'' |- | '''Check Database Structure Before Import''' | ''Cleared'' | ''Cleared'' |- | rowspan="2" | | colspan="2" | The set of customization packages applied to the source instance when a snapshot was taken is the different from the set of packages applied to the destination instance when the snapshot is to be imported. | '''Include Data From Custom Columns''' | The scenario is not applicable. | ''Cleared'' |- | '''Check Database Structure Before Import''' | The scenario is not applicable. | ''Selected'' |} An imported snapshot is stored in the database, and you can restore the data from the snapshot whenever you want.

The contents of the snapshot is the data from SQL database tables that are included in the snapshot. The list of tables to be included to a snapshot is defined by a content option (or export mode) that you select when you take a snapshot. There is a predefined set of options that you can select in the '''Export Mode''' box of the '''Create Snapshot''' dialog box. If the predefined options do not suite your need, for example, for data security reasons, you can configure and add custom options.{br}

In this topic you will read about how snapshot configuration is stored and can be modified.[anchor|#section_Snapshot_Contents]
==Snapshot Configuration Storage==
The contents of a snapshot for each of content options (except the ''Full'' option) is defined by a corresponding snapshot configuration file with the ''.esc'' extension. Usually these files can be located in '''%Program Files%\Acumatica ERP\&lt;instance name&gt;\App&#95;Data\SnapshotConfigs''', where ''&lt;instance name&gt;'' is the name of the application instance website. 
==Creation of Custom Configurations==
When the system is creating a snapshot it goes through all tables specified in a configuration file and copies all data with no restrictions or validation. If you want to preserve some data that you consider sensitive—for example, user passwords and settings for connecting with third-party applications—we recommend you to create your own snapshot configuration files to preserve such data, down to SQL table fields. You can either exclude tables and table fields from snapshots or replace data in table fields with predefined values. For examples of configuration settings, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Snapshot_Sensitive_Data|Examples of Sensitive Data Preservation in Snapshots].((({S:Warn}We do not recommend modifying predefined snapshot configuration files, during upgrade these files will be replaced with the next predefined version.
)))
You can save a copy of predefined configuration file with a custom name to the same location where the other configuration files are stored and modify it contents to suite your needs. When you are ready with the modifications, you click '''Restart Application''' on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_10|Apply Updates] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203510|SM203510]) form and your custom content option becomes available for a snapshot creation.((({S:Warn}Make sure that all users of your website are warned about the site restart so that they can save all documents. 
)))

Protection of sensitive data is critical to organizations and to users. Which data must be protected depends on many factors, including regulation (which is often mandatory), organization policy, contractual obligations, and user expectations. Because the snapshots may copy data you identify as sensitive, Acumatica ERP provides a way to exclude such data from the snapshots. You can preserve the data from particular SQL tables down to particular table fields by configuring snapshot configuration files. Use the following examples to better understand and configure snapshot configuration files.{br}{TOC}
==Prohibit Export and Import of User Records==
If you don&rsquo;t want to export and import user records except for one user (''Baker''), add the following section to the snapshot content file.{{{{&lt;Include table="Users" preserve="true"
condition ="where Username &lt;&gt; 'Baker'"&gt;
&lt;/Include&gt;
}}}}
==Export User Records with a Predefined Password==
If you want to export user records but change users&rsquo; passwords to a predefined value (''password''), add the following section to the snapshot content file.{{{{&lt;Include table="Users" preserve="true"
&lt;ResetColumn name="Password" value="password" /&gt;
&lt;/Include&gt;
}}}}
==Prohibit Export and Import of Blob Provider Settings==
If you don&rsquo;t want to export and import Blob Provider settings, add the following section to the snapshot content file.{{{{&lt;Include table="BlobStorageConfig" preserve="true"/&gt;
&lt;Include table="BlobProviderSettings" preserve="true"/&gt;
}}}}
For more information on Blob Provider settings, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_File_Attachment_Management|File Attachment Management].
==Prohibit Export and Import of the Key of Blob Provider Settings==
To export and import all Blob Provider settings except for the provider key, add the following section to the snapshot content file.{{{{&lt;Include table="BlobStorageConfig" preserve="true"/&gt;
&lt;Include table="BlobProviderSettings" preserve="true"
condition ="where Name &lt;&gt; 'Key'"&gt;
&lt;/Include&gt;
}}}}
==Replace the Key of the Blob Provider Settings on Export and Import==
To export and import all settings of the Blob Provider but empty the provider key value, add the following section to the snapshot content file.{{{{&lt;Include table="BlobStorageConfig" preserve="true"/&gt;
&lt;Include table="BlobProviderSettings" preserve="true"
condition ="where Name = 'Key'"&gt;
&lt;ResetColumn name="Value" value="" /&gt;
&lt;/Include&gt;
}}}}
