*[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_File_Attachment_Management|File Attachment Management]

User roles in Acumatica ERP are sets of access rights to system objects designed for convenient management of access for users with similar responsibilities in the system. In Acumatica ERP, a system object to which access rights can be set up can be a particular form, container of form elements, form element, or wiki. ((({S:Hint}For details about managing access to wikis, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Wiki_Access_Setup|Wiki Access Management].
))){br}{TOC}
==Learning Objectives==
In this chapter, you will learn how to do the following:[anchor|#ul_dmx_2lv_pr]
*Create a user role and specify access rights to system objects for this role
*Modify access rights to system objects for a copy of an existing role
*Give access to only several forms in the system and revoke access to all other system objects.
*Review access rights a role has to system objects

==Applicable Scenarios==
You create or modify user roles in the following cases:[anchor|#_7165d0ed-fbf9-4bca-b563-a0155c7a9310]
*When you, as a implementation consultant, initially implement Acumatica ERP for your client and the predefined set of roles does not suite your client needs.
*When you, as a system administrator, was notified that a security policy of your company has changed and after revision of the current set of roles, you need to modify access rights to Acumatica ERP elements.
*When you, as a system administrator, was notified about opening a new position in your company, for which the current set of roles does not cover the job description.

==Restriction Levels==
A user role in Acumatica ERP is a set of access rights to system objects. By defining access rights for a system object you set a restriction level a user with the role will have for this object. The restriction level defines set of operations a user may perform with the object. The highest restriction level allows a user to perform any operation with an object up to its deletion and the lowest denies access to an object.{br}

The system objects are a particular form, container of form elements, form element. In Acumatica ERP, the system objects are grouped in a tree with nodes, where a tenant is the first-level node with the workspaces nested under it. Each workspace, in it is turn, can nest multiple forms, that nest containers of form elements, that nest form elements. {br}

 Acumatica ERP has the ''Not Set'' restriction level that is specific for the system. The ''Not Set'' restriction level indicates that all roles have access to a form including its nested objects until at least one role is assigned any other restriction level to this form. All roles with the ''Not Set'' level are then denied access to the form. For example, you created a new generic inquiry and added it to a workspace. By default, all roles in the system will get the ''Not Set'' restriction level to the inquiry. If you change the level to any other for at least on role, users that are not assigned with this role will not have access to the inquiry. [anchor|#_7303dc59-8564-4f86-8ef9-73242753aa0a]{br}

The set of restriction levels available for the system objects depends on the object type. For some objects, you can specify more granular level, for others either allow or deny the access. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\User_Roles_Access_Levels|User Roles: Restriction Level Options].
==Access Propagation and Inheritance==
In Acumatica ERP, the system objects are grouped in a tree with nodes. Each node is a system object that can nest other objects. Access rights either propagated to the nested objects or nested objects inherit access rights from their parents. The hierarchy of nesting is the following: [anchor|#_218c8917-51c2-49ca-b7e4-091f725a00ce]
#''Tenant'': A tenant node nests all workspaces configured in the system. The system propagates access rights set to a role for this node to all workspaces in the tenant.
#''Workspace'': A workspace node nests all forms added to the workspace. The system propagates access rights set to a role for this node to all forms within the workspace.
#''Form'': A form node may or may not nest several containers with the form elements. Nested containers inherit access rights set to a role for a form.
#''Form container'': A container node nests form elements, such as boxes and actions. Nested elements inherit access rights set to a role for a container. 
#''Form element'': An element node is on the lowest level of objects hierarchy and inherits access rights from its parent container. 

The propagation and inheritance mechanism allows saving time and simplifies setting of access rights to system objects. You can change propagated or inherited rights for any object anytime, that is, change a restriction level received from a parent object. For specifics about restriction levels of a particular system object, see [HelpRoot_Administration\User_Roles_Access_Levels|User Roles: Restriction Level Options].
==Predefined Roles==
For ease of defining and administering roles, Acumatica ERP provides a set of predefined roles, which is expanded with every major release of Acumatica ERP. Predefined roles are always supplied with the system and cannot be deleted. We recommend using the predefined roles, while setting user access to the system during implementation. Create a new role, only if there is no a predefined role that suites your needs. For details on available predefined roles, see [HelpRoot_Administration\User_Roles_Built_In_Roles|User Roles: Predefined Roles].((({S:Warn}If a predefined role mostly works for you, but needs a bit of tweaking, we recommend copying the role and do needed changes. Otherwise, all your changes will be deleted during an upgrade.
)))
==Role Planning==
Organizations have different kinds of valuable information that needs protecting, like financial documents, customer and vendor information. Different employees need access to different subsets of this information to perform their duties. Before you start planning the set of user roles, we recommend to make sure that job roles and responsibilities in your company are clearly defined. The job responsibilities of a user define access to forms, records, and operations on the records. {br}

While planning the set of roles, take into account objectives of internal control procedures implemented in your company, like preventing and detecting fraud, completeness and accuracy of financial records, safeguarding assets, timely preparation of financial statements. For example, to minimize the risk of errors and fraud, duties associated with cash handling are often segregated. Also, segregation is recommended for duties related to documents recording and further processing, as well as conducting reconciliations and preparing financial statements.{br}

We highly recommend performing planning of access configuration when the system is initially implemented and in case of changing a security policy of an organization. For detailed recommendations, see [HelpRoot_Administration\User_Roles_Planning_Concept|User Roles: Planning Access Configuration].
==Role Creation==
You use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form to create a role. By default, a newly created role has the ''Not Set'' restriction level for all system objects. The nested objects (containers and elements) have the ''Inherited'' access level. ((({S:Hint}We recommend using some naming conventions for the user roles that you create or copy from predefined roles. 
)))
As Acumatica ERP is supplied with the set of predefined roles, for which access rights were set up (that is, restriction levels to different objects were changed from ''Not Set'' to restriction level appropriate for a role), a newly created role will be denied access to most system objects.[anchor|#_ecfe6b9f-8b94-4d86-b911-ca09009f8ad2]((({S:Danger}The ''Not Set'' restriction level indicates that all roles have access to a form including its nested objects until at least one role is assigned any other restriction level to this form. This role can be any role in the system. All roles with the ''Not Set'' level are then denied access to the form.
)))
To set up access rights to multiple system objects for multiple roles, you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_20|Access Rights by Screen] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201020|SM201020]) form. The form allows you to see restriction level that other roles have to a system object. This information can be useful when you set up access to this object to a particular role as it may affect access of other roles, if the ''Not Set'' restriction level is specified for them.{br}

To set up access rights to multiple system objects for an individual role, you use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201025|SM201025]) form.((({S:Hint}The process of defining task-based roles requires in-depth knowledge of both the organization&rsquo;s business processes and the Acumatica ERP approach to security. 
)))[anchor|#section_wgv_hbd_yl]
==Role Access Modification==
During ongoing maintenance of Acumatica ERP, you may have tasks to change users&rsquo; access rights to some system objects. To modify a role access you use either the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_20|Access Rights by Screen] or [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_25|Access Rights by Role] form.{br}

You may take different approaches in configuring user access: assigning a user with a single role or with a combination of roles. This may affect how a role modification will affect an individual user access.{br}

If you do not use role combination the modification of a role will affect access for all users with the role assigned. If you use role combination the modification of a role may differently affect users with the role assigned. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\User_Roles_User_Access_Level_Calculation|User Roles: Calculation of Restriction Level for a User].{br}

Before proceeding to role modification, we recommend collecting detailed information about the role configuration and users assigned with the role. For details on access management reports, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Managing_User_Access_Reports_Inquiries|User Access: Related Report and Inquiry Forms].

Designing a system security requires a thorough planning and preparation. User access configuration should support business processes without exposing the company to undue risks. That is, a user should have only the access rights necessary to perform typical tasks, that are clearly stated in the job description of the user.{br}
In this topic you will read about approaches we recommend you to consider while planning user access to the system. ==Full Access Role Approach== Small companies usually do not require a complex user access configuration that includes multiple roles and strict segregation by job responsibilities. Employees are usually multitasking and restricting access to the system configuration is usually enough. In this case, you can design roles individually for a person or for a group of people. For example, for a company with 5 to 10 employees, you can configure two roles as follows:[anchor|#_00043e42-b601-4551-b693-a878ba7d262a] *''Administrator'': Users with this role have complete access to all system objects in the system regardless functional area. *''Regular User'': Users with this role have complete access to system objects of multiple functional areas, except for areas related to the system security and user management.
==Access Tier Approach== Midsized companies need more complex user access configuration as more people need to access company&rsquo;s data, but job responsibilities usually are defined and segregated more clearly.{br}
Let&rsquo;s consider the predefined set of roles that regulates access to finance-related functionality. Roles are grouped by functional areas, such as general ledger, accounts payables, accounts receivables and others. Across these areas, we can say that in this set there are three tiers of access for each functional area: Admin, Clerk, and Viewer. The following table summarizes the access difference for these tiers.[anchor|#_f2610da1-412f-453d-a7a0-1388c96a3b7c] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Access Tier !width="20%" ! Adding and Processing Records !width="20%" ! Deleting Records !width="20%" ! Configuration Settings !width="20%" ! Reports and Inquiries |- | Admin | Full access | Full access | Full access | Full access |- | Clerk | Full access | Full access | View only | View only |- | Viewer | View only | View only | View only | View only |} With such configuration you might consider giving to a user a set of roles either from the Clerk or Admin tiers and use roles from the Viewer tier for employees who perform internal or external audit. For example, you assign to a senior accountant all roles from the Admin tier, thus giving complete access to the whole finance-related functionality. For the accountant assistants you assign roles from the Clerk tier according to their responsibilities.{br}
Also, you might consider combination of roles from different tiers. For example, a user who is doing reconciliation will need to view reports and inquiries from general ledger and accounts payable functional areas. So, in addition to CA Admin role that allows doing reconciliation, you assign to the user the AP Viewer and GL Viewer roles. ==Granular Role Approach== Aside having three tiers of access (Admin, Clerk, and Viewer), we recommend creating roles that allows performing granular, but sensitive tasks. For example, suppose that a senior accountant with a role from the Admin tier usually reprints checks. During their vacation the senior accountant passed this responsibility to their deputy who has a role from the Clerk tier. If you have a role that allows performing only reprinting checks, you can temporary assign this role to the deputy user, instead of giving a role from the Admin tier. {br}
The other solution for securing access to reprinting checks is to create a role specifically for reprinting checks and restrict access to reprinting for all other roles. In this case, you can assign this role to only approved users regardless their tier of access.

Users are assigned to roles, and you give these roles the appropriate access rights to system objects— forms, containers of form elements, form elements, and wikis. By defining access rights for a system object you set restriction level a user will have for this object. With Acumatica ERP, you can control access down to the control of form elements, such as buttons, text boxes, and check boxes. {br}
This topic describes the restriction levels available to different system objects.{br}{TOC} ==Access to a Workspace== In Acumatica ERP, you do not set up access to a particular workspace itself. Instead, by setting access rights (that is restriction level) for a workspace, you set up access for all the nested objects. If you change the access rights to any nested object of a workspace, the system will change the access rights to ''Multiple Rights'' at the workspace level. {br}
The system displays a workspace with ''Multiple Rights'' in the main menu. On the workspace dashboard, the system displays only forms for which access is not restricted for a particular user.{br}
Keep in mind that a form may belong to multiple workspaces. If you set access to one of these workspaces (that is, to all forms in the workspace), the system will assign to a form that belongs to multiple workspaces the restriction level set most recently for one of these workspaces. The system will then change the access for other workspaces to which the form belongs to the ''Multiple Rights'' option, if these workspaces had a different access rights. For example, the [HelpRoot_FormReference\AP_40_20_00|Vendor Details] form can be accessed from the '''Payables''' and '''Purchases''' workspaces. Both workspaces have the ''Granted'' restriction level for the ''Purchasing'' role. You change the level for the form under the '''Payables''' workspace to ''Revoked''. The system displays the new level for the form under the '''Purchases''' workspace and changes access to ''Multiple Rights'' for both workspaces.{br}
The following table summarizes the restriction levels that roles can have to all forms that belong to a particular workspace of Acumatica ERP.[anchor|#table_fzs_pqd_wj] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Restriction Level !width="80%" ! Description |- | ''Multiple Rights'' | Means that a role has different restriction levels to the nested objects of a workspace. If you change the level for the workspace, the system will automatically apply the new level to all nested objects. |- | ''Not Set'' | Allows all roles to have access to all forms in a workspace until ''Revoked'' or ''Granted'' level is set to the workspace for at least one role. After that, a role with the ''Not Set'' level is denied access to the forms in the workspace. |- | ''Revoked'' | Denies the role access to all the forms in a workspace. That is, all forms will get the ''Revoked'' restriction level. For users with the role, the workspace and its forms do not appear in the main menu. |- | ''Granted'' | Allows the role complete access to all the forms in a workspace. That is, all forms will get the ''Delete'' restriction level. You can, however, limit or revoke access to particular forms within the workspace for the role. In this case, the system will change the access rights for the workspace to ''Multiple Rights''. |}((({S:Warn}You can set up access rights to individual forms in the '''Hidden''' node (which cannot be accessed from the main menu), but not to the node itself. ))) ==Access to Reports and Generic Inquiries== A workspace may include multiple reports and inquiries along with the Acumatica ERP forms. Available restriction levels depend on tools used to develop a report or an inquiry.[anchor|#_f1709db3-76c7-4646-be4b-3829ef59be4b] *Reports built with the Report Designer application and inquiries created using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_80_00|Generic Inquiry] form have the same list of available restriction levels that roles can have to workspaces. *Reports built with the Analytical Report Manager toolkit and inquires developed using C# have the same list of available restriction levels that roles can have to forms. [anchor|#section_whj_vn2_wj] ==Access to a Form== Within each workspace, you can set the access rights that roles have to Acumatica ERP forms, which affects what users with those roles can access. The restriction level to the form is inherited by the entities and records that can be created by using the form. [anchor|#table_y1t_pqd_wj] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Restriction Level !width="80%" ! Description |- | ''Not Set'' | When assigned to all roles, allows all roles to have access to the form until the restriction level is changed to any other level for at least one role. After at least one role has been assigned another level, access to the form is denied for a role with the ''Not Set'' level. |- | ''Revoked'' | Denies the role access to the form and its functionality. |- | ''View Only'' | Gives the role restricted access to the form and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the form and any records associated with the form (in drop-down lists on other forms). This level forbids users with the role to edit details about any record, create new records or entities of the type, and delete records. |- | ''Edit'' | Gives the role restricted access to the form and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the form, select records, and edit details about any record. This level forbids users with the role to create new records or entities of the type, and to delete records.{br}
The '''Clipboard''' button is available on the form toolbar for users with the role. |- | ''Insert'' | Gives the role restricted access to the form and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the form, select records, edit details about any record, and create new records or entities of the type. This level forbids users with the role to delete records.{br}
The '''Clipboard''' and '''Insert''' buttons are available on the form toolbar for users with the role. |- | ''Delete'' | Gives the role complete access to the form and its functionality. This level encompasses the capabilities of the ''View Only'', ''Edit'', and ''Insert'' levels, while also giving users with the role the ability to delete records. For users with the role, the '''Clipboard''', '''Insert''', and '''Delete''' buttons are available on the form toolbar. |} ==Access to Containers of Form Elements== Each form includes containers of elements, such as nested forms, tabs, and grids. Each container includes multiple elements and actions. You can restrict access to any of these containers on the form. The restriction level a role has to the container is inherited by the entities and records created by using the container, if applicable. For example, if you permit access for a user role to a grid, a user with this role can access all records in this grid. By default, containers inherit restriction level from the form to which they belong.{br}
[anchor|#_8832ae06-4664-4c72-b270-6012730a91aa] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Restriction Level !width="80%" ! Description |- | ''Inherited'' | Indicates that the role&rsquo;s access to the container was not explicitly specified and is inherited from its form. |- | ''Revoked'' | Denies the role access to the container and hides it from the form for users with the role. These users will not see the container on the form. |- | ''View Only'' | Gives the role restricted access to the container and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the container and any records associated with the container (in drop-down lists on other forms), if applicable. The level forbids users with the role to edit details about any record, create new records or entities of the type, and delete records, if applicable. |- | ''Edit'' | Gives users with the role restricted access to the container and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the container, select records, and edit details about any record, if applicable. The level forbids users with the role to create new records or entities of the type, and delete records, if applicable. |- | ''Insert'' | Gives the role restricted access to the container and its functionality. This level allows users with the role to view the container, select records, edit details about any record, and create new records or entities of the type, if applicable. This level forbids users with the role to delete records, if applicable. |- | ''Delete'' | Gives the role complete access to the container and its functionality. This level encompasses the capabilities of the ''View Only'', ''Edit'', and ''Insert'' levels, while also giving users with the role the ability to delete records, if applicable. |} ==Access to Form Elements== By default, the restriction level a role has to the form elements and actions is inherited from the container of form elements to which elements and actions belong. In most cases, a restriction level for a container is not explicitly specified and is set to ''Inherited''. Thus, before changing a restriction level to an element or an action you should explicitly specify a restriction level for the parent container. Then you can set access to the form elements and actions.[anchor|#table_kgx_3h2_wj] {| class="checklist" | width="100%" |- !width="20%" ! Restriction Level !width="80%" ! Description |- | ''Inherited'' | Indicates that the role&rsquo;s access to the element was not explicitly specified and is inherited from its container of form elements. |- | ''Revoked'' | Denies the role access to the element and hides the element. A user with the role will not see the element on the form. |- | ''View Only'' | Makes the element read-only for users with the role. A user with the role will see the element on the form but will not be able to use it. |- | ''Edit'' | Allows the use of the element for users with the role. |}

In Acumatica ERP, the business date is displayed in the info area. The business date is the date that the system will insert by default into the records that you add to the system. By default, the current date is set as the business date. {br}

Some companies might want to restrict the availability of changing the business date in the system. This can be done to avoid issues with generated documents that have the dates of closed periods inserted into them. {br}

By default, all users can change the business date in the Acumatica ERP system.{br}{TOC}
==Configuring Permissions to Change the Business Date==
To restrict the availability to change the business date, you should enable the ''Secure Business Date'' feature on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] ([~/?ScreenId=CS100000|CS100000]) form. This will make the Business Date menu button generally unavailable for clicking and editing.{br}

In your company, only some employees might need the ability to change the business date in the system. You can grant these users access rights to change it by assigning the ''BusinessDateOverride'' role to them on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_10|Users] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201010|SM201010]) form or the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_10_05|User Roles] ([~/?ScreenId=SM201005|SM201005]) form.((({S:Warn}This role is available only if the ''Secure Business Date'' feature is enabled on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CS_10_00_00|Enable/Disable Features] form.
)))
==Incrementing of the Business Date==
The system handles the incrementing of the business date at midnight individually for each user session: The date is automatically incremented at midnight only if you have not modified the business date in any way during your user session. {br}

That is, if you do not change the business date during your user session and your session is active at midnight, the system increments the date. If you have modified the business date somehow, the system will keep the changed date as long as your user session is active.

To access Acumatica ERP, an individual must have a user account in the system and a user role assigned to the account. Each account includes a login, a password, and other properties, such as the user’s first and last name, email address, password policy options, and set of roles that control user&rsquo;s access to the system objects. {br}{TOC}
