The development of automatic data processing has made it necessary to consider protecting sensitive information. In certain highly regulated industries, companies must implement auditing to address identity-management concerns related to compliance issues. Regulations such as Sarbanes-Oxley (SOX), the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA), and the Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) all have extensive requirements on auditing user identity and access to system resources.{br}
If your company must comply with such regulations, wants to ensure accountability and the ability to track user actions in the system, or wants to implement sound auditing procedures, you can use the field-level auditing available in Acumatica ERP.{br}
By using the field-level auditing functionality, you can monitor and record user actions on Acumatica ERP forms as they are recorded in the system. The audit trail holds records of every change users have made on the monitored forms, such as changes to documents and their properties, modifications to customer accounts or employee records, and changes in security policies. You can also see who made the changes and when they took place.{br}{TOC} ==Managing Access to Field-Level Audit Feature== Before you start configuring and turning on auditing for specific forms, you must enable the ''Field-Level Audit'' feature. To give users the ability to configure, turn on, and turn off auditing of forms, as well as view the audit trails, you assign them the ''Field-Level Audit'' role and give them access to the forms used to manage field-level auditing. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__con_Managing_Field_Level_Audit_Access|Management of Access to Field-Level Audit Functionality]. ==Configuring and Turning on Auditing of a Form== If you want to maintain a record of user activity on any form, you can configure and turn on auditing of the form. Granular auditing is configured, turned on, and turned off on a per-form basis. After the form audit is configured, you can quickly turn on and off auditing of the form. When you turn on the audit, every time a user makes changes to a document associated with the form and clicks '''Save''', a record is added to the audit trail the system maintains for the form. This record contains the details of the modification, including who modified the document, what changes were made, and when the changes occurred.{br}
For more granular control, you can perform auditing of individual database tables associated with the forms and specific database table fields. You can audit entire database tables or only certain database table fields, such as the fields associated with the interface elements on the form. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__How_to_Configure_Field_Level_Audit|To Configure and Turn On Field-Level Auditing for a Form]. ==Viewing an Audit Trail== When auditing is turned on for a form, you can select a document and view the changes made to the document directly from the form by clicking '''Audit History''' on the '''Tools''' menu. The audit trail shows who modified the document and when, what form was used, when the modification took place, and what changes were made.{br}
Also, you can view all the changes made in the database tables of the audited form. The audit trail shows the user who modified the document, the date and time of the update, and the details of the modification of the selected database table. You can filter the modifications that you view in any audited database table by user and by date range. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__How_to_view_Field_Level_Audit|To View a Field-Level Audit Trail]. ==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_55_20|Audit] ([~/?ScreenId=SM205520|SM205520]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_55_30|Audit History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM205530|SM205530]) *[HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_55_10|Audit] ([~/?ScreenId=SM205510|SM205510]) *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__How_to_Configure_Field_Level_Audit|To Configure and Turn On Field-Level Auditing for a Form] *[HelpRoot_Administration\SM__How_to_view_Field_Level_Audit|To View a Field-Level Audit Trail]

After you configure and turn on auditing for a form, you can view the audit trail for each document created or modified by using the audited form. You can view the audit trail of a selected document directly from the audited form, or you can use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_55_30|Audit History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM205530|SM205530]) form to view the audit trail of any document created by using any audited form. Also, you can use the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_55_20|Audit] ([~/?ScreenId=SM205520|SM205520]) form to view the list of forms in the system for which auditing has been configured. ==To View Changes in a Document from the Form==[anchor|#ol_yj3_bw4_qj] #Open the applicable form and select or navigate to the document whose modifications you want to view. #On the form toolbar, on the '''Tools''' menu, click '''Audit History'''. #:This opens the '''Audit History''' page in a new tab where you can see the list of changes made to the selected document. For each change, you can see the time of the change and the user who changed the document. #:((({S:Warn}If auditing is turned off, the '''Update History''' dialog box opens instead. In this dialog box, you can see information about the creation and last modification of the selected document. You can click '''Enable Field Level Audit''' to turn on auditing of the form. ))) #In the '''Audit History''' page, navigate to the change whose details you want to see. #Click the '''Changes''' arrow to view the detailed data of the modification. #:((({S:Warn}Click '''Expand All''' to view the details of all modifications or click '''Collapse All''' to hide these details. Also, you can use the browser functionality to search for a specific word or phrase on the screen or to print the screen. )))
