==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_Dev_Customization\CG_GL_Items_Screens_UserDefinedFields|To Add a User-Defined Field to a Customization Project]

By using Acumatica ERP, you can configure automatic notifications about various events in the organization, such as training sessions, work meetings, conference calls, and trade shows. Users create events and invite leads, contacts, and customers to attend them, and the system sends invitations to the potential attendees specified for the event. Also, the system reminds users about the event and notifies attendees if you make any changes to the event or cancel it.{br}{TOC} ==Event-Related Settings== By using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\EP_20_40_70|Event Setup] ([~/?ScreenId=EP204070|EP204070]) form, you can configure automatic notifications about events to be held by your company employees. You can configure either simple (built-in) notifications or template-based notifications that allow users to send personalized emails. A template can include placeholders that are replaced by each addressee's personal data, such as the first and last names and position, when the system generates event notification emails.{br}
You can create the following templates: [anchor|#ul_u3r_jwy_w3] *''Invitation template'': This template can be used to send personalized email invitations to the persons listed on the '''Attendees''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CR_30_60_30|Event] ([~/?ScreenId=CR306030|CR306030]) form. If the user adds new potential attendees to the list after sending initial invitations and saves the event, the system will prompt the user to send invitations to the added potential attendees. *''Rescheduling template'': This template can be used if the event date or time has been changed. Emails based on the template are sent to all invited persons automatically once the event is shifted to a new start time. *''Cancellation template'': This template is used if the invitation to the event is canceled for a particular potential attendee (for instance, if the event planner sent the invitation to this person in error) or for all potential attendees.
==Creation of New Events== Users can view existing events by using the [HelpRoot_FormReference\EP_40_41_00|Events] ([~/?ScreenId=EP404100|EP404100]) form. Clicking the '''Add Event''' button on the table toolbar invokes the [HelpRoot_FormReference\CR_30_60_30|Event] ([~/?ScreenId=CR306030|CR306030]) form (as a pop-up window), which lets you create a new event. {br}
When creating an event, the user may configure a ''reminder'' for it, specifying the day and time when all invited attendees will be reminded about the event (by the '''Automatic Reminder''' dialog box popping up). ==Event-Related Notification Emails== If a user creating an event specifies potential attendees, notification emails will be sent at the following times to the specified parties: [anchor|#ul_rz2_zht_w3] *When the event is being saved for the first time: To all potential attendees *When new attendees are added: To only newly added attendees *When the event is rescheduled: To all potential attendees *When the event is canceled: To all potential attendees *When the invitation is canceled: To the selected potential attendees
==Related Articles== *[HelpRoot_FormReference\EP_20_40_70|Event Setup] ([~/?ScreenId=EP204070|EP204070])

In Acumatica ERP, various business processes are executed, which may require the monitoring of particular activities and conditions in the system. To eliminate the need for a user to monitor the business processes, you can configure the system to monitor the company data and to perform an action (such as sending an email notification or performing the instructions defined by an import scenario) or multiple actions in the system. {br}{TOC} ==Learning Objectives== In this chapter, you will learn how to do the following:[anchor|#ul_dmx_2lv_pr] *Create business events to monitor data changes of selected set of database fields and notify involved parties about the changes *Create business events to monitor events on a particular data-entry form and notify involved parties about the events *Configure the system to monitor fulfillment of a set of conditions on schedule and perform specified actions
==Applicable Scenarios== You use business events in the following cases:[anchor|#_7165d0ed-fbf9-4bca-b563-a0155c7a9310] *You need to monitor specific data being changed in the system and make the system to perform some actions based on the change. For example, in contract management, you can configure the system to send an email notification to the customer when the customer&rsquo;s contract is activated. *You need to monitor the meeting of particular conditions, which the system checks for at the schedule you specify and make the system to perform some actions in this case. For example, in the management of opportunities, you can configure the system to send an email to the owner of an opportunity when it is one month from its estimated close date and the opportunity hasn&rsquo;t been updated for more than seven days. The system performs this monitoring once a day. *You need to help your employees and selected external contacts to track key developments that occur within the organization. Some examples include the following: **A sales manager may want the system to notify a customer contact when a sales order has been shipped to the customer. **Your company might want to tell customers about changes in their blanket purchase orders. **A manager may want to know when a specific purchase order has received all the required approvals. **A credit manager may want to know when a sales order is created for a particular customer that is approaching its credit limit. **A customer service manager may want to be informed when a new employee is assigned a case of a specific type, to give the employee assistance with this type of case.
==Types of Business Events==[anchor|#_779e6a00-5bff-46aa-af3a-d7fc15f65705] To configure the system to monitor a business process, on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form, you define a ''business event'' that relates to this business process and that causes the system to perform an action or multiple actions in the system. {br}
The business event can be one of the following:[anchor|#_a23c3105-3cb8-4120-be64-00620fe5c2ef] *Data change: You create a business event of the ''Trigger by Record Change'' type. *Occurrence of a particular event (fulfillment of a set of conditions), which the system checks for at the schedule: You create a business event of the ''Trigger by Schedule'' type.
Then for each business event you specify a source for monitoring, conditions to trigger actions, and actions (event subscribers) to be performed when conditions are met. If you want the system to monitor a business process at schedule, you additionally specify a schedule for the event. ==Source for Monitoring== The system needs a source to monitor data changes or the occurrence of particular events. The source defines a set of database fields whose values are to be monitored. The system triggers the event processing, if a value changes or a set of values met specified conditions.{br}
In Acumatica ERP you can use the following sources to retrieve the data you want to monitor:[anchor|#_7bab1d57-2b23-4784-a711-20bde46970e8] *Generic inquiry: You create a generic inquiry to retrieve data from the database fields that you want the system to monitor. Also, you could instead use an existing generic inquiry if one exists that retrieves the needed data. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Business_Events_GI_Source_Concept|Business Events: Generic Inquiry as Source]. *:((({S:Warn}You can use a generic inquiry as a data source for all available types of business events and subscribers. ))) *Data-entry form: You can use a data-entry form as a source of data that you need to monitor, for example, [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_30_10_00|Invoices and Memos] ([~/?ScreenId=AR301000|AR301000]), [HelpRoot_FormReference\AR_30_30_00|Customers] ([~/?ScreenId=AR303000|AR303000]), and [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]). The created business events act as notifications for the events on the forms. For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Business_Events_Data_Entry_Source_Concept|Business Events: Data-Entry Form as Source]. *:((({S:Warn}[anchor|#_6a5cefa3-421f-422c-910a-62c380663554]You can use a data-entry form as a source for business events of the ''Trigger by Record Change'' type only. Also, using an import scenario as a subscriber is not available if such source is selected. )))
You start creation of a business event with specifying a generic inquiry or a data-entry form that defines the data for the system to monitor, in the '''Screen Name''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form. For a generic inquiry, you can also select an advanced filter (if one has been defined for the it). For details on advanced filters, see [HelpRoot_ReportingTools\GI_Reusable_Filters_Mapref|Managing Advanced Filters]. ==Conditions to Trigger Actions== After you have specified a data source for the event, you configure the conditions when the system should perform actions related to the business process, on the '''Trigger Conditions''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] form. You can configure the conditions that are applied to any of the following: [anchor|#_b28880ac-077b-495e-8dfc-563493797c77] *The results of the monitoring before the data change (the old field values). *The results of the monitoring after the data has been changed (the new field values). *The comparison of these results. That is, the condition can check whether a field value has been changed, or a record has been added, removed, or updated.
The action is performed if the values of monitored fields have been changed according to the specified conditions.{br}
In the '''Raise Event''' box of the Summary area of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] form, you can also select how the system should generate the business event: for each record that satisfies the trigger conditions or for the whole set of records that satisfy the trigger conditions. ==Actions to Perform on Event Occurrence (Event Subscribers)== To define the actions that the system should perform in the system once the business event has occurred, you specify the ''subscribers'' of this business event, on the '''Subscribers''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] form. A subscriber of a business event is an entity in the system that the system processes when the business event occurs. The following types of subscribers are supported.[anchor|#_e24f6f46-0346-4880-8a8e-d4e19bf94862] *''Import Scenario'': If the subscriber is an import scenario, the system executes the sequence of instructions defined by the import scenario that you have specified for the business event. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Business_Events_Import_Scenarios_Concept|Business Events: Import Scenarios]. *:((({S:Warn}The ''Import Scenario'' type is not available for a business event if a data-entry form is selected as a source for monitoring. ))) *''Email Notification'' * ''Mobile Push Notifications'' * ''Mobile SMS Notifications'' *:If the subscriber is an email, a push notification or an SMS notification, the system sends the needed emails, push or SMS notifications based on the settings of the notification template that you have specified for the business event. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Business_Events_Emails_Concept|Business Events: Email Notifications], [HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Business_Events_Push_Concept|Business Events: Push Notifications] and [HelpRoot_Administration\SA_Using_Business_Events_SMS_Concept|Business Events: SMS Notifications].
You can configure a subscriber before you create a business event, then you select a subscriber that has been configured; if needed, you can select multiple subscribers (one in each row). {br}
To create a new subscriber, you click '''Create Subscriber''' and click the menu command corresponding to the type of the subscriber, which causes the system to open a corresponding Acumatica ERP form (for an email, push or SMS notification to a mobile device) or the dialog box and form (for an import scenario script) to create the subscriber.{br}
If you have specified multiple subscribers on the '''Subscribers''' tab for the business event, you can select the '''Stop on Error''' check box in the row of a subscriber to direct the system to process subsequent subscribers in the list only if no error has occurred while the system was processing the current subscriber. ==Schedules to Monitor Business Process== To dictate when the system should check whether the data meets the specified conditions, you configure a schedule or schedules. You can monitor a business process on schedule only if a generic inquiry is selected as data source in the '''Screen ID''' box of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] form.{br}
On the '''Schedules''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] form, you select a schedule that has been configured; if needed, you can select multiple schedules (one in each row).{br}
If the needed schedule has not been configured beforehand, you click '''Create Schedule''', which causes the system to open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_50_20|Automation Schedules] ([~/?ScreenId=SM205020|SM205020]) form. On this form, you configure the schedule by which the system should check the conditions on the data for monitoring. {br}
For details on configuring schedules, see [HelpRoot_Administration\SM__mng_Schedules|Managing Schedules].

You create a generic inquiry to retrieve data from the database fields that you want the system to monitor. Also, you could instead use an existing generic inquiry if one exists that retrieves the needed data. {br}

In this topic, you will read about recommendations and limitations on using a generic inquiry as a source for monitoring.{br}{TOC}
==General Recommendations==
A generic inquiry to be used as basis for monitoring a business process should be as simple as possible. We recommend that you check whether only the needed fields and tables are used in the generic inquiry you have decided to use. If the already-existing inquiry uses any fields and tables that are unnecessary for your specific business event, you should instead create a new inquiry and use it.{br}

Business events do not support generic inquiries that have grouping specified on the '''Grouping''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_80_00|Generic Inquiry] ([~/?ScreenId=SM208000|SM208000]) form. Thus, we recommend that you avoid unnecessary multiple joins and joins to the same tables. In most cases, you can exclude from the generic inquiry all the tables that are not used on the '''Results Grid''' tab of the corresponding generic inquiry.((({S:Warn}You must add all key fields of used tables to the '''Results Grid''' tab of the corresponding generic inquiry. You can make them hidden, if you do not need to view them on the inquiry form. For details on discovering key fields, see [HelpRoot_ReportingTools\GI_Manual_Configuration_of_Relations_Concept|Getting Data from Multiple DACs: Manual Configuration of Relations Between Tables].
)))
For details on working with generic inquiries, see [HelpRoot_ReportingTools\SM__MNG_Managing_Generic_Inquiry|Managing Generic Inquiries].
==Recommendations for Push Notifications==
If you plan to send push notifications to users of the Acumatica mobile app on mobile devices, make sure that the generic inquiry you have selected includes the <tt>NoteID</tt> data field for the entity that you plan to display when a user taps a notification on the mobile device. {br}

For example, suppose that you want to notify employees about new opportunities assigned to them, and when an employee taps this notification, the app should display the new opportunity. In this case, you should add the <tt>NoteID</tt> data field for the object <tt>CROpportunity</tt> on the '''Results Grid''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_80_00|Generic Inquiry] ([~/?ScreenId=SM208000|SM208000]) form.

You can use a data-entry form as a source of data that you need to monitor. The created business events act as notifications for the events on the forms.{br}

In this topic you will read about ways to create business events to monitor data changes made on a particular entry from and limitations applied to the business events functionality for this data source.{br}{TOC}
==Ways to Create Business Events for a Data Entry Form==
You can create a business event directly from a data-entry form which data changes you need to monitor. To create business events for an entry form, you open the form and click '''Business Events''' on the form title bar.{br}

In the '''Business Events''' dialog box that opens, you click '''Create Business Event''', enter the name for the event in the dialog box, and click '''OK'''. The system navigates you to the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form, with the data-entry form selected as a data source.{br}

Alternatively, you can start creation of a business event with specifying the data-entry form in the '''Screen Name''' box on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form.
==Limitations of Using Data-Entry Form==[anchor|#_a52f07a2-013e-4f3e-80e2-ebb13616eccd]
You can use a data-entry form as a source for business events of the ''Trigger by Record Change'' type only. Also, using an import scenario as a subscriber is not available if such source is selected.

You can configure the system to perform actions when a change of the data related to a business process has occurred. In this topic, you can find information about the processing of the business events related to data changes.{br}{TOC}
==Business Event Processing==
When a business event is configured and is active—that is, the '''Active''' check box is selected for it on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form—the system starts monitoring data changes made to the data included in the generic inquiry form or provided by a data-entry form. {br}

If a record has been changed, the system checks whether the record satisfies the conditions specified on the '''Trigger Conditions''' tab. If the record satisfies the conditions (which means that the business event has occurred), the system processes the subscribers of the event that are specified on the '''Subscribers''' tab. {br}

After all subscribers of the business event have been processed, the system saves information about the processing of the business event, which you can view on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form.{br}

The following diagram illustrates the configuration and processing of business events related to record changes.[anchor|#_cf3804c6-77f3-477d-97f5-c637b7b428b6][anchor|#_201de822-5ef5-4b49-8512-02a4675a1b05][image:UserGuide/Images/BusinessEventByRecordChange.png|popup|The processing of a business event related to record changes|450px]

You can configure the system to perform actions based on the occurrence of particular events, which the system checks for at the schedule you specify. In this topic, you can find information about the processing of this type of business events.{br}{TOC}
==Business Event Processing==
When a business event is configured and is active—that is, the '''Active''' check box is selected for it on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form—and the next schedule execution date comes, the system executes the generic inquiry. If the generic inquiry returns any data, the system checks whether the returned records satisfy the conditions specified on the '''Trigger Conditions''' tab. If there are records that satisfy the conditions (which means that the business event has occurred), the system processes the subscribers of the event that are specified on the '''Subscribers''' tab. {br}

After all subscribers of the business event have been processed, the system saves information about the processing of the business event, which you can view on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form.{br}

The following diagram shows how business events checked for on a schedule are configured and processed.[anchor|#_2732e838-e4cc-4ff9-8765-0c9da2ece6d8][anchor|#_08d1453e-875f-4a0d-8542-dbb7e171fd24][image:UserGuide/Images/BusinessEventBySchedule.png|popup|The processing of a business event monitored on a schedule|450px]

If a subscriber to a business event is an email notification, when the business event occurs, the system sends an email (or multiple emails) to particular recipients, based on the settings of the notification template that you have specified for the business event.{br}

In this topic, you will read about creating a notification template to be used as a subscriber of a business event.{br}{TOC}
==Creating an Email Notification Subscriber==
The easiest way to create an email notification for a business event is to do so while you are creating the event on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form: On the table toolbar of the '''Subscribers''' tab, you click '''Create Subscriber''' > '''Email Notification'''. This causes the system to open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_03|Notification Templates] form with the correct value selected in the '''Screen Name''' box{br}

Also, you can open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_03|Notification Templates] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204003|SM204003]) form and configure a notification template that can be selected as a subscriber of the ''Email Notification'' type. On this form, you must specify the sender, the recipients of the notification emails, and the template for the email message. Also, in the '''Screen Name''' box, you specify the generic inquiry or data-entry form of the business event. 
==Using Placeholders for Email Notification Template==
In the notification template you define on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_03|Notification Templates] form, you can use placeholders for the values of the data fields, provided by a form or a generic inquiry in the '''Screen Name''' box of the form. If values are available in a record created with a data-entry form or in the results of the generic inquiry, the system retrieves these values and uses them to compose an email for sending.{br}

You can use placeholders to define the following settings:[anchor|#_f47f9a31-3a36-48b0-a1f0-656790342b1d]
*Recipients of the email in the '''To''', '''CC''', and '''BCC''' boxes
*The subject of the notification template in the '''Subject''' box
*The body of the notification template on the '''Message''' tab

For details, see [HelpRoot_Administration\EM__con_Notification_Templates|Notification Templates].
==Attaching an Email as Activity==[anchor|#_7f4138a8-f9af-41e9-a74a-8ff66f47564a]
For a notification template that is used as a subscriber of a business event, you can specify whether the system should link a sent email as activity of the ''Email'' type to an entity defined in the system. For example, a customer, a vendor, a contact or a document.{br}

To attach a sent email as activity to an account or a contact, you specify the data fields that contain a business account ID (<tt>BAccountID</tt>) or a contact ID (<tt>ContactID</tt>) in the '''Link to Account''' or '''Link to Contact''' boxes, respectively. The system creates an activity of the ''Email'' type and links this activity to the specified business account or contact. {br}

To attach a sent email as activity to a system entity you use one of the following setting:[anchor|#_877bcb68-c9ac-4580-9c48-ac9332a26a7e]
*'''Attach Activity''': You select this check box to direct the system to link a sent email as activity of the ''Email'' type to an entity that was created using a data-entry form specified in the '''Screen Name''' box. 
*:For example, if the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SO_30_10_00|Sales Orders] ([~/?ScreenId=SO301000|SO301000]) form is specified in the '''Screen Name''' box and the notification template is used as subscriber of a business event configured to monitor data changes for this form, the system links the activity to a sales order that triggered the event.
*'''Link to Entity''': You specify in this box a data field for a unique identifier of an entity (<tt>NoteID</tt>) to direct the system to link a sent email as activity of the ''Email'' type to an entity that is in the results of a generic inquiry specified in the '''Screen Name''' box.

You can then view the activity on the '''Activities''' tab of the corresponding form or in the '''Tasks & Activities''' dialog box, which opens if you click '''Activities''' on the form title bar. For details about activities, see [HelpRoot_CRM\CRM_Mktg_Managing_Emails_Activities_GeneralInfo|Managing Emails and Activities: General Information].
==Attaching a Report to Email Notification==
For notification templates that used as subscribers of business events, you can select a report or multiple reports to attach to the email on the '''Attached Reports''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_03|Notification Templates] form. On the tab, you can specify the report format and parameters. If the parameter values are not specified, the default value of parameters will be used when the report is generated.{br}

On the right pane, in the '''Reports Attached by Report ID''' table, in the '''Report ID''' box, you can select the report to be attached. In the '''Report Format''' box, you can select the format of the attached report: ''Excel'', ''HTML'', or ''PDF''. Selecting the ''HTML'' format makes the '''Embedded''' check box available. When this box is selected, the report will be inserted in the email body.{br}

On the right pane, in the '''Report Parameters''' table, for each added report you specify parameters to be passed to the report at the moment of the report generation process.{br}

Alternatively for an added report, you can select the '''Use Event as Data Source''' box on the left pane, the system can pass the business event data to the report, rather than selecting data from the database at the moment of the report generation process. The '''Use Event as Data Source''' check box is available and can be selected only if there are common tables in generic inquiry (specified in the '''Screen Name''' box) and in the report. If the check box is selected the '''Source Table''' box becomes available and contains the source tables for selection.{br}

Additionally, you can select a report to be attached in the '''Attach Report Opened by Action''' box. The system uses the list of reports available under the '''Reports''' action on the form toolbar of the data-entry from specified in the '''Screen Name''' of the form.
==Processing an Email Notification Subscriber==
When the business event occurs and the system processes the subscriber of the ''Email Notification'' type, the system extracts the values of the fields specified for placeholders of the template (from the results of the generic inquiry that satisfy the conditions) and inserts these values into the email. The system then sends the email or emails to the recipients.{br}

If the notification has been sent successfully, the system considers the subscriber to be successfully processed and adds a record on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form. If any error has occurred during the processing of the notification template, the system displays the error on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] form for the business event.

If a subscriber to a business event is a push notification, when the business event occurs, the system sends a push notification or multiple push notifications to the mobile devices of particular recipients, based on the settings of the notification template that you have specified for the business event.{br}

In this topic you will read about configuring and processing of push notifications created as subscribers of business events.
==Configuring Push Notification as Subscriber==
The easiest way to create a push notification for a business event is to do so while you are creating the event on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form: On the table toolbar of the '''Subscribers''' tab, you click '''Create Subscriber''' > '''Mobile Push Notification'''. This causes the system to open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] form with the ''Push'' option selected in the '''Delivery Method''' box and the correct value selected in the '''Screen''' box.{br}

Also, you can open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204004|SM204004]) form and configure a notification template that can be selected as a subscriber of the ''Mobile Push Notification'' type. On this form, you must specify the push delivery method, the description, the recipients of the notifications, and the template for the message. Also, in the '''Screen''' box, you specify the generic inquiry of the business event. {br}

In the notification template you define on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] form, you can use placeholders for the values of the form elements. As the placeholders, you can use the data fields available in the results of the generic inquiry of the business event as follows:[anchor|#_9bff3da5-d8a6-4ff2-b526-bc8da8a248c7]
*To specify the recipients of the notification (in the '''To''' box), you can use the data fields (as the placeholders, separated with semicolons) that hold user identifiers and whose values are retrieved when the business event occurs. For example, if you need to monitor cases and send notifications to assignees, you can use a placeholder for the identifier of the assignee, such as {{((CRCase_ownerID!PKID))}}. 
*You use the needed fields to specify which entity should be opened by the mobile app after a user taps the notification (in the '''Destination Entity ID''' box). Make sure that the {{NoteID}} data field is present in the results of the generic inquiry for the entity. For example, suppose that you selected ''Sales Orders'' in '''Destination Screen ID''' and want to open a particular order for the user; then you need to select the {{NoteID}} data field for the {{SOOrder}} object in '''Destination Entity ID'''.
*To specify the subject ('''Title''') of the notification template, you can use any data fields whose values are retrieved when the business event occurs. For example, the subject could be {{Opportunity ((CROpportunity_opportunityID)) has been assigned to you}}. 
*In the body of the notification template (on the '''Message''' tab), you can click '''Insert Data Field''' on the formatting toolbar to insert as a placeholder any data field whose value is retrieved when the business event occurs. Also, you can click '''Insert Previous Data Field''' to insert as a placeholder any data field whose value was retrieved before the business event occurred. You can use this ability to demonstrate how the value of the data field has changed, for example, a case status has changed from ''New'' to ''Open''.

==Processing a Push Notification as Subscriber==
When the business event occurs and the system processes the subscriber of the ''Mobile Push Notification'' type, the system extracts the values of the fields specified for placeholders of the template (from the results of the generic inquiry that satisfy the conditions) and inserts these values into the notification. The system then sends the push notification or notifications to appropriate mobile devices of the recipients.{br}

If the notification has been sent successfully, the system considers the subscriber to be successfully processed and adds a record on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form. If any error has occurred during the processing of the notification template, the system displays the error on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] form for the business event.

If a subscriber to a business event is a mobile text notification, when the business event occurs, the system sends a mobile text notification (or multiple text notifications) to the mobile devices of particular recipients, based on the settings of the notification template that you have specified for the business event.{br}

In this topic you will read about configuring and processing of SMS notifications created as subscribers of business events.{br}{TOC}
==Configuring an SMS Notification as Subscriber==
The system uses an SMS service account configured on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_35_35|SMS Providers] ([~/?ScreenId=SM203535|SM203535]) form to send mobile text notifications. You can configure an account with the Amazon or Twilio service provider.{br}

The easiest way to create a text notification for a business event is to do so while you are creating the event on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form: On the table toolbar of the '''Subscribers''' tab, you click '''Create Subscriber''' > '''Mobile SMS Notification'''. This causes the system to open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] form with the ''SMS'' option selected in the '''Delivery Method''' box and the correct value selected in the '''Screen''' box.{br}

Also, you can open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] ([~/?ScreenId=SM204004|SM204004]) form and configure a notification template that can be selected as a subscriber of the ''Mobile SMS Notification'' type. On this form, you must specify the SMS delivery method, the service provider, the description, the recipients of the notifications, and the template for the message. Also, in the '''Screen''' box, you specify the generic inquiry of the business event. {br}

In the notification template you define on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_40_04|Mobile Notifications] form, you can use placeholders for the values of the form elements. As the placeholders, you can use the data fields available in the results of the generic inquiry of the business event as follows:[anchor|#_40b737ba-3e86-4836-ae58-8a13fd766d1f]
*To specify the recipients of the notification (in the '''To''' box), you use the data fields (as the placeholders, separated with semicolons) that hold user phone numbers and whose values are retrieved when the business event occurs. Also, you can specify phone numbers explicitly, separated with semicolons. 
*:For example, if you want to send a text about a shipment confirmation to a customer, you can use a placeholder for the identifier of the customer&rsquo;s phone number, such as {{((SOShipment_customerID!DefContactID!Phone1))}}.
*In the body of the notification template (on the '''Message''' tab), you can click '''Insert Data Field''' on the formatting toolbar to insert as a placeholder any data field whose value is retrieved when the business event occurs. Also, you can click '''Insert Previous Data Field''' to insert as a placeholder any data field whose value was retrieved before the business event occurred. 
*:For example, suppose that you would like to notify a customer that the status of the case has changed to another one. You insert the {{((CRCase_status))}} data field, which represents the placeholder of the case status and whose value will be retrieved when the business event occurs. To show the previous status of the case, you click '''Insert Previous Data Field''' and select the same data field; the system will insert the placeholder with the {{PREV}} function, which in our example is {{PREV((CRCase_status))}}. When the event occurs, the system retrieves the value that the field had before the event has occurred. 

==Processing an SMS Notification as Subscriber==
When the business event occurs and the system processes the subscriber of the ''Mobile SMS Notification'' type, the system extracts the values of the fields specified for placeholders of the template (from the results of the generic inquiry that satisfy the conditions) and inserts these values into the notification. The system then sends the text notification or notifications to the mobile devices of the recipients.{br}

If the notification has been sent successfully, the system considers the subscriber to be successfully processed and adds a record on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form. If any error has occurred during the processing of the notification template, the system displays the error on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] form for the business event.

If a subscriber is an import scenario, when the business event occurs, the system executes on the target Acumatica ERP form the sequence of instructions defined by the import scenario that you have specified for the event. With the import scenario, you can perform any action defined on the target Acumatica ERP form, such as release of a document.{br}

In this topic you will read 
==Configuring an Import Scenario as Subscriber==
You configure a subscriber of the ''Import Scenario'' type on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_60_25|Import Scenarios] ([~/?ScreenId=SM206025|SM206025]) form. We recommend that you open this form to create the subscriber from the '''Subscribers''' tab of the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_30_20_50|Business Events] ([~/?ScreenId=SM302050|SM302050]) form: You click '''Create Subscriber''' > '''Import Scenario''' on the table toolbar and specify the name of the scenario in the '''Create Import Scenario Subscriber''' dialog box, which opens. {br}

When you enter the name and click '''OK''' to close the dialog box, the system automatically creates on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_60_15|Data Providers] ([~/?ScreenId=SM206015|SM206015]) form a data provider of the ''Business Process Provider'' type for the import scenario (if the provider has not been created earlier for the generic inquiry of the business event). For this provider, the ''ScreenID'' parameter on the '''Parameters''' tab is set to the generic inquiry of the business event. The provider has two schema objects on the '''Schema''' tab: ''Results'' and ''PreviousResults''. Each object includes all fields of the results of the generic inquiry. The ''Results'' object returns the values of these fields when the business event occurs. The ''PreviousResults'' object returns the values of these fields before the business event has occurred. {br}

When the data provider has been created, the system opens the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_60_25|Import Scenarios] ([~/?ScreenId=SM206025|SM206025]) form with the import scenario name and the data provider specified. On the form, you complete creation of the import scenario by specifying the following:[anchor|#_817444ab-02a3-42b6-b456-a5fcd1dcaf9c]
*In the '''Screen Name''' box, the target Acumatica ERP form (which can be any Acumatica ERP form) on which the system should execute the sequence of instructions when the business event occurs.
*In the '''Provider Object''' box, the ''Results'' provider object or the ''PreviousResults'' provider object, depending on whether you want the system to extract the values before the business event has occurred or the values when the business event has occurred. The system uses the specified results of the generic inquiry to perform the sequence of instructions on the target form. 
*On the '''Mapping''' tab, the mapping of the import scenario—that is, the sequence of instructions that the system should perform on the target form when the business event occurs. When you are mapping fields, you should first map the key fields: the fields that the system uses to distinguish records that belong to different documents. After you have mapped the key fields, you should map other fields in the order in which you would fill them in on the form. At the end of the mapping of the scenario that creates or updates data in the system, to save the record to the database, you have to insert a row with the ''&lt;Action: Save&gt;'' action. For details about import scenario mapping, see [HelpRoot_Integration\IS__mng_Scenario_Mapping|Configuring Scenario Mapping].

You can also specify other parameters of the import scenario and source and target restrictions. For more information about import scenario configuration, see [HelpRoot_Integration\IS__mng_Configuring_Import_Scenarios|Configuring Import Scenarios].
==Processing an Import Scenario as Subscriber==
When the business event occurs and the system processes the ''Import Scenario'' subscriber, the system extracts the values (either the values before the business event has occurred or the values when the business event has occurred, depending on the provider object you specified for the import scenario) of the fields of the generic inquiry results and uses them as the source fields of the import scenario. The system executes on the target Acumatica ERP form the sequence of instructions defined by the import scenario. {br}

If the scenario has been executed successfully, the system considers the subscriber to be successfully processed and adds a record on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] ([~/?ScreenId=SM502030|SM502030]) form. If any error has occurred during the processing of the import scenario, the system displays the error on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_50_20_30|Business Event History] form for the business event.

