Now you can view the same wiki article both in Acumatica ERP and on Self-Service Portal. ==To Hide a Wiki From the Acumatica ERP Main Menu==
#Open the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_20_05|Wiki] ([~/?ScreenId=SM202005|SM202005]) form. #In the '''ID''' box, select the wiki that you want to hide from the main menu. #In the '''Site Map Location''' box, delete the location. #On the form toolbar, click '''Save''' to remove the wiki from the Acumatica ERP main menu. #Reload the webpage in the browser to apply changes in the site map of Acumatica ERP.

This article describes what searches are available in Acumatica Wiki and how to perform the searches. When you search wikis, you can do a quick search or a full-text search. To perform a search, you can use the '''Search''' box (in the navigation pane) and the Search form. {br}
For more information on searching in Acumatica ERP, see [HelpRoot_Interface\Search_Options_and_the_Search_Form|Search]. ==To Perform a Quick Search== When you perform a quick search, the system searches article properties, such as article IDs, categories, names, summaries, and keywords. It does not search the text of articles. ((({S:Hint}For each article, a wiki author can specify a concise summary, an appropriate category (such as ''reference, overview,'' or ''procedure''), and a list of keywords, so that wiki users can quickly find the information they need, even if they do a quick search. ))) To perform a quick search, do the following: #In the navigation pane, in the '''Search''' box, type a word, a part of a word, or a phrase you&rsquo;re searching for. #Click '''Search'''. #On the Search form, click '''All Wikis''' to open the [HelpRoot_Interface\SE_00_00_40|Search Form] ([~/?ScreenId=SE000040|SE000040]). On the form, you will see a list of articles in all wikis whose properties contain the search word or phrase you entered in Step 1. #Optional: Click the '''All Wikis''' arrow and select a wiki to see a list of articles in the selected wiki whose properties contain the search word or phrase you entered in Step 1. #Optional: If you selected a particular wiki, click '''Advanced''' and then select check boxes for the wiki-specific categories you want the system to search. (This option is unavailable for the '''All Wikis''' scope.)
==To Perform a Full-Text Search== For a full-text search, the system searches article properties as well as the full text of articles. The full-text search takes longer and may return articles that do not contain the information you hope to find. To ease the process of finding the required information, start by searching for a more specific word or phrase and then search for broader words or phrases if needed. {br}
To perform a full-text search, do the following: #In the navigation pane, in the '''Search''' box, type the word, part of a word, or phrase you&rsquo;re searching for. #Click '''Search'''. #On the Search form, click '''All Wikis''' to open the [HelpRoot_Interface\SE_00_00_40|Search Form] with the list of articles in all wikis whose properties contain the search word you entered. #Optional: On the Search form, click the '''All Wikis''' arrow and then select a particular wiki to search within it, or select '''All Wikis''' to again search in all wikis. This step defines the scope of the search. #Select the '''Full-text search''' check box. #Optional: If you selected a particular wiki, click '''Advanced''' and then select check boxes for the wiki-specific categories you want the system to search. (This option is unavailable for the '''All Wikis''' scope.) #Click '''Go''' to start the search.

In Acumatica Wiki, you can use the Wiki Editor form to edit the entire article—its text and properties. Alternatively, you can edit a section of the article or the entire text of the article.{br}
To format the text, you use wiki markup, an easy-to-understand syntax that uses special wiki markup elements. You can manually type the wiki markup or click the buttons on the Formatting toolbar to have the system insert markup elements for you. For more information, see [HelpRoot_Administration\DM__con_Wiki_Using_Wiki_Markup|Wiki Markup Reference]. ==To Edit the Article and Its Properties== You can edit the entire article and its properties by using the Wiki Editor form for the article. To open the Wiki Editor form, click '''Edit''' on the wiki toolbar.{br}
For more information, see [HelpRoot_FormReference\DM__con_Wiki_Wiki_Editor_Form_for_Articles|Wiki Editor Form for Articles]. ==To Edit a Section== To edit an article section, which consists of the text beneath a heading until the next same-level heading, do the following: [anchor|#ol_ynw_fr2_vg] #Open the wiki article you want to edit. #Click '''Edit''' to the right of the section heading. #Edit the section text. #:((({S:Hint} You cannot edit article properties when you&rsquo;re editing a section. ))) #On the formatting toolbar, click '''Save''' to save your changes or click '''Cancel''' to exit the Wiki Editor form without saving changes.

You can create links to places in the current article, to other articles in the same wiki, and to external websites. These links help users quickly access additional information they might need. ==To Navigate Within an Article== With a lengthy article, you might want to give users the ability to quickly navigate within the article. To do this, you first insert anchors to mark the beginnings of sections and other positions in the article to which you want to redirect users. You then insert anchor links, which users can click to easily navigate to the defined anchors. {br}
To define an anchor, do the following:[anchor|#ol_qw1_5d2_lj] #Open the article. #On the wiki toolbar, click '''Edit Current Article''' to open the article in the Wiki Editor form. #Click the place within the article where you want to create the anchor. #Add the anchor by using the following general syntax:{{{{[Anchor|#<i>AnchorID<i>] }}}} #:where ''AnchorID'' is the unique identifier you define for the anchor within the article. It can include any combination of numbers and uppercase and lowercase letters. For example, you can use sequential numbers or abbreviated versions of section names as IDs.
You can create as many anchors as you like in the article, but each ''Anchor ID'' must be unique.{br}
After you have added the anchor, you can insert as many links to the anchor as you need. To insert an anchor link, do the following:[anchor|#ol_xdb_tg2_lj] #With the article still open in the Wiki Editor form, click the place within the article where you want to add the anchor link. #Add the anchor link by using the following syntax:{{{{[#<i>AnchorID<i>|<i>LinkText<i>] }}}} #:where ''AnchorID'' is the identifier that you defined for the anchor, and ''LinkText'' is the text to be displayed as the link. The user clicks this link to navigate to the anchor.
For example, to enable users to return to the top of the article from a place within the article, create an anchor at the top of an article by adding the following syntax at the beginning of the article: {{{{[Anchor|#Top] }}}} Then add the following syntax to the article in the place where you want to create the link to the top of the article: {{{{[#Top|Return to the top] }}}} Now, each time users click the {{Return to the top}} link, they navigate to the top of the article. ==To Add Links to Articles and Websites== You use wiki links to give users the ability to quickly access other articles within the Acumatica ERP instance.{br}
To add a link to another article, do the following: [anchor|#ol_t5w_qgg_lj] #Open the article to which you want to add the link. #Open the article for editing. Do one of the following: #*On the wiki toolbar, click '''Edit Current Article''' to open the entire article in the Wiki Editor form. #*Click '''Edit''' to the right of the section to which you want to add the link. #On the formatting toolbar, click '''Link'''. This opens the '''Wiki Link Editor''' dialog box. #In the '''Wiki Link Editor''' dialog box, specify the link parameters: #*To configure a link to another article, do the following: #*#In the Link Type box under the '''Wiki text''' box, select '''Article'''. #*#In the box to the right of the Link Type box, select the article you want to add a link to. #*#Optional: In the '''Caption''' box, type the text of the link, which the user will click to navigate to the article. #*To configure a link to an external web site, do the following: #*#In the Link Type box under the '''Wiki text''' box, select '''URL'''. #*#In the box to the right of the Link Type box, type or paste the URL of the external website. #*#In the '''Caption''' box, type the text of the link. #Click anywhere in the '''Wiki text''' box to update the link, and then copy the link. #Click '''OK''' to close the dialog box. #Click the position in the text where you want the link to be, and then paste the link. #In the formatting toolbar, click '''Save'''. #:((({S:Warn}If you opened the article in the Wiki Editor form, alternatively, you can click '''Save''' in the Wiki Editor form toolbar to save your changes and exit the editing mode. ))) #Check the link displayed in the article by clicking the link text.
In Acumatica Wiki, you use the following basic format for a link:{{{{[ArticleID|LinkText] }}}} where ''ArticleID'' is the identifier of the article, and ''LinkText'' is the text of the link. The user clicks on this word or phrase to navigate to the article for which you specify the identifier.{br}
Here are some examples of wiki links: *{{[Glossary]}}: This text is displayed as a link. *{{[Glossary|This is a link to the Glossary]}}: This link is displayed with a custom link text ([HelpRoot_Interface\Glossary|This is a link to the Glossary]); clicking the link opens the Glossary article. *{{[~/Pages/GL/GL202500.aspx|Chart of Accounts]}}: This link redirects the user to a form in the General Ledger module of Acumatica ERP.
By using external links, you can redirect users to external websites and mail-to links. Here are some examples of external links:[anchor|#ul_qcl_2ng_lj] *{{[http://google.com]}}: The system displays this link as a string with the external link icon: [http://google.com/]. *{{[mail@server.com]}}: The system displays this text as a mail-to link: [mail@server.com]. *{{[mail@server.com|Contact us]}}: The system displays this string as a mail-to link with a custom link text: [../UserGuide/mail@server.com|Contact us].

At times, you might want to illustrate the concepts or ideas in an article. To do this, you can import graphics to add them to articles. In the process, you can specify a variety of display options. [anchor|#section_jr1_qbc_tj] ==To Import a Graphic File== Before you import your file, make sure that the size of your file does not exceed the maximum file size allowed and that the type of file is allowed. You can check the maximum allowable file size and the valid file extensions on the [HelpRoot_FormReference\SM_20_25_50|File Upload Preferences] ([~/?ScreenId=SM202550|SM202550]) form.{br}
To import a graphic file for an article, do the following: [anchor|#ol_xr1_qbc_tj] #Open the article to which you want to add the graphic. #Open the article for editing. Do one of the following: #*Click '''Edit''' to the right of the section to which you want to add the graphic. #*On the wiki toolbar, click '''Edit Current Article''' to open the entire article in the Wiki Editor form. #On the formatting toolbar, click '''Attach File'''. #:((({S:Warn}Alternatively, if you opened the Wiki Editor form, you can click '''Attach''' on the Wiki Editor form toolbar. This opens the '''File Upload''' dialog box. ))) #In the '''File Upload''' dialog box, click '''Browse''' to find the file, select the file, and then click '''Upload'''. This opens the '''File Link Editor''' dialog box. # In the '''File Link Editor''' dialog box, specify the following options:[anchor|#image_bhc_z53_5g][image:UserGuide/Images/Adding_Pictures_Adding_PicturesFile_Link_Editor.gif|popup|File Link Editor Dialog Box|350px] #*In the '''Type''' box, select one of the following display options: ''Not Set'', ''Thumb'', ''Frame'', or ''Border''. #*In the '''Alignment''' box, select one of the following alignment options: ''Not Set'', ''Right'', ''Left'', or ''Center''. #*In the '''Caption''' box, enter the caption for the graphic. #*In the '''Size''' box, enter the display size (in pixels) of the graphic to be displayed. #:For more information, see the [[#section_mcz_rys_kj|Customize a Graphic] section of this article. #Click anywhere in the '''Wiki text''' box to update the link, and then copy the link. #Click '''OK''' to close the dialog box. #Click on the position in the text where you want to insert the graphic, and paste the link. #Click '''Save'''. #Check the graphic displayed in the article, and correct the options if needed.
