column, which shows the time taken by each step, and find the row with the biggest value in this column, as shown in the following screenshot.[anchor|#_31364e97-fa99-4b92-b67c-dfe988e8c938][image:UserGuide/Images/SQLProfilerDialogBox.png|popup|SQL Profiler dialog box|300px] #Double-click on this row to see the actual SQL statement, an example of which is shown in the following screenshot.[anchor|#_72f92926-2e0a-48ca-951b-6283c56db44e][image:UserGuide/Images/SQLStatement.png|popup|SQL statement|250px] #Copy and paste the statement into SQL Server Management Studio, run the query with the Execution Plan enabled, and see whether any suggestions are provided by the SQL Server. #:The following screenshot demonstrates SQL Server suggesting that the problem is a missing index.[anchor|#_538317c2-fd3f-4c7b-b641-d27b7dc70bf8][anchor|#_2a72b1ea-3c9e-4509-9de5-6993e5906f00][image:UserGuide/Images/MissingIndex.png|popup|SQL Server suggestion|450px] #Report the issue to the Acumatica support team, as described in [HelpRoot_Administration\how_Troubleshoot_Performance_Step6|Step 6: Submit a Case to Acumatica Support]. You can save the Request Profiler log to an Excel file by clicking '''Export to Excel''' on the table toolbar on the Request Profiler form. #:((({S:Warn}You can perform the solution suggested by SQL Server as an interim fix after consultation with the Acumatica support team. However, we recommend that such issues are always reported via a support case for a permanent solution. ))) [anchor|#_fef30de7-dc42-43f4-aca5-14f7f616d1ad] ==2. Collect Additional Information from the Logs== You should collect the information from the needed log files depending on the situation, which can be one of the following:[anchor|#_33626c12-94b4-4597-99c3-92c56cb7c276] *[[#_8fb8c886-591d-4e6b-a292-34a9e85a9d43|The performance slowdown appeared after an update] *[[#_2505615e-ba3f-4ee6-ac6d-fb0222d14d5c|Your site is completely non-responsive or extremely slow] *[[#_ca9df984-b2b3-4164-bb95-334